!NEW! COBOL SUPPORT HELP FILE
        There is a new help file for COBOL support.  It is
        automatically installed when you install the COBOL support
        module.

!FLASH! MULTI-EDIT AND WINDOWS
        It was recently discovered that the driver SHARE.EXE (we've
        tested the version that comes with DOS version 6.0 and 6.2),
        which is very commonly used for Windows, has a serious memory
        overwrite bug related to setting the attributes of open files.
        One of the ways that this is manifested is that it causes DOS
        programs running in a window to suddenly switch into full
        screen during file loading or saving.  It is suspected that
        less benign behavior (like crashing) is possible.  Version
        7.00f has a work-around that seems to have rectified the
        problem.  Please use SHARE.EXE only if you absolutely must.  We
        can't be sure if there are not other bugs as well.

!NEW! TAGGING FILES IN THE FILE OPEN PROMPT:
        Most file prompts for opening files now support file tagging.
        File prompts for saving files do NOT support file tagging.  To
        tag files, simply move into the Directory List box, and press
        the space bar (or click with the right mouse button) to tag or
        un-tag the desired files.  You may navigate through directories
        and tag files as needed.  After files have been tagged,
        pressing the <ENTER> or selecting OK with the mouse will open
        all of the tagged files.

!NEW! LOAD MULTIPLE FILES WITH A FILE LIST
        From the command line, you may now use the /@filename switch to
        use a "list file" to specify the files to be loaded.  For
        example, if you had a file called FILES.LST that contained the
        following:

                TEST1.S
                README.DOC
                WOW.C

        And then you start me with the commandline:

                ME /@FILES.LST

        Then the three files that where in FILES.LST will be loaded.

!NEW! PRINTING OPTIONS
        The print dialog box has 2 new check boxes:

                [ ] print in Hex

        This allows you to print your file in hexadecimal notation,
        just like it is displayed in hex mode (menu - Text - heX mode).
        The print dialog box automatically senses when you are in a hex
        window and checks this for you.  You can print in hex, however
        from a normal window as well.  You can also override the
        default for this by setting the global variable:

                global_int("@PRN_HEX_MODE")

        See the section below titled "!NEW! STARTUP MACRO STUFF" for
        more details about this global variable.

                [ ] fIlter control chars

        If this box is checked, all characters in the file whose ASCII
        code is less than 32 (20h) will be replaced by a space
        character.  This guards against your printer "choking" on
        control characters as most normally do.  If you wish to have a
        different character replace the control characters, you can use
        the global variable:

                global_int("@PRN_FILTER_CHAR")

        There is also a global variable that can force this check box to
        be enabled as a default:

                global_int("@PRN_FILTER")

        See the section below titled "!NEW! STARTUP MACRO STUFF" for
        more details about these global variables.


!NEW! STARTUP MACRO STUFF

                global_int("@PRN_HEX_MODE")
        If this is set to 1, the default for the hex printing check box
        in the print dialog box will be turned off.  If 2, it will be
        turned on.  In either case, the automatic detection of display
        mode (hex vs normal) is disabled.

                global_int("@PRN_FILTER")
        If this is set to 1, the default for the filter control chars
        check box in the print dialog box will be turned on.

                global_int("@PRN_FILTER_CHAR")
        If set > 0, it will override the ASCII code of the character
        used as the substitute character when the filter control chars
        check box in the print dialog box is turned on.  A value of -1
        will cause the null character to be used.

                global_int("PRN_LINE_NUMBERS")
        Set this one if you want Multi-Edit to print files with line
        numbers by default.  A value of 1 or 2 behaves the same when
        printing the entire file.  A value of 1 causes block printing
        to put line numbers relative to the top of the block.  A value
        of 2 causes blocks to have line numbers relative to the top of
        the file.

                global_int("@MOU_SCRL_BAR_DELAY")
        If this is set > 0, it will introduce a delay in milliseconds
        when the mouse button is held down on a scroll bar.

                global_int("@NO_BEEPS")
        If set to 1, it will disable most of the beeps that occur.
        Note: this will not disable the beep() macro command, just the
        macro BEEPS which is used for almost all beeps in the system
        macros.

                global_int("@PRN_USE_WIN_TERM")
        If set to 1, the line terminator sent to the printer will
        be the same as the line terminator in the current window.
        Otherwise, the line terminator will always be CR,LF.

!NEW! BRIEF EMULATION STUFF
        We've improved the emulation of Brief windowing and bookmarks.
        Bookmarks will now be restored between sessions (if restore is
        enabled).

        For those who prefer the old style (6.10 and before) Brief
        windowing, that is actually Multi-Edit style windowing, we've
        added a new #define to BRIEF.S:

                #define B_WINDOW_STYLE 1

        If you change it to 0, and recompile BRIEF.S, the Brief
        windowing operations will be mapped to Multi-Edit window
        operations.

CONVERTING YOUR SETUP FROM 6.x TO 7.0
	See the file CONV_700.DOC.

ME386.EXE
	ME386.EXE is special version of Multi-Edit that has been
	compiled and specially optimized for 386 (or greater)
	processors.  If you are running on a 386, 486 or Pentium based
	machine, we highly recommend that you use ME386.EXE instead of
	ME.EXE.  You can even rename ME386.EXE to ME.EXE.  Please note:
        ME386.EXE will not run under current releases of Windows NT, as
        Windows NT only emulates 286 mode for DOS apps.

MOUSE SUPPORT IN > 80 COLUMN VIDEO MODES
        Multi-Edit now fully supports the mouse in wide screen video
        modes.  If you experience any problems with Multi-Edit and your
        video mode, or mouse, try starting ME with the /MF switch.

MULTI-FILE SEARCH DOES NOT SUPPORT CROSS-LINE REGULAR EXPRESSIONS
        Currently multi-file search does not support regular
        expressions that span lines.  Normal search with a file that
        is already loaded into Multi-Edit does.  This limitation will
        be addressed in the future.

IMPORTING MACROS YOU HAVE WRITTEN
	Most macros compiled under 6.0 and 6.1 are fully compatible
	with 7.0.  All you need to do is copy the .MAC files to the MAC
	subdirectory under the main Multi-Edit directory.  Most of you
	will want to copy the .S files into the SRC subdirectory also.

	See the Converting Macros section of this file for information
	on differences and compatibility issues.

MULTI-EDIT PRO MACRO SOURCE
	The macro source and macro debugger for Multi-Edit Pro are
	installed automatically.  If you do not want the macro source
	(which takes up about 1.5 meg of disk space) you may delete it.
	The only file in the SRC directory that you really need is
	STARTUP.S.

IMPORTING ADD-ONS (Evolve, Multi-Tags, NameIt!, 50+ Macros)
	Copy the appropriate files from the old into the new directory.
	If a file is in the MAC, SRC, HELP, or DOC subdirectory under
	the old main Multi-Edit directory, make sure the file ends up
	in that same subdirectory under the new main Multi-Edit
	directory.

	Here is a list of the files for each package including the
	directory (assuming the old Multi-Edit is in C:\ME):

	EVOLVE 6.1: - Note:	It is highly recommended that users
				currently using Evolve 5.1 upgrade to
				Evolve 6.1, which works only with
				Multi-Edit 6.10b or later.

		C:\ME\EV*.* C:\ME\EVOLVE\*.* C:\ME\MAC\EV*.MAC
		C:\ME\MAC\STDLIBR.MAC
		C:\ME\HELP\EV*.HLZ

		Plus... After you copy all the files, run the macro:
		EV_INST^EV_MOD_STARTUP

		Network version users:  The user specific files will
		be as follows (xxx = user id):
			C:\ME\xxx.USR\EV*.*

	MULTI-TAGS:
		Multi-Tags is now a standard part of Multi-Edit
		professional.  You need to install the new version of
		Multi-Tags from scratch.  You may then copy over your
		METAGS.DB configuration file.

		PLUS... Don't forget to check to see if Multi-Tags is
		in your user menu and the keys are assigned.  The macro
		command for Multi-Tags, in case you have to run it
		manually is:

			METAGS

		Also, depending on the way you use Multi-Edit and
		Multi-Tags, there may be some .TAG files in the old
		main Multi-Edit directory.  If so, copy them over.

		Network version users:  The user specific files will
		be as follows (xxx = user id):
			C:\ME\xxx.USR\METAGS.DB

	NAMEIT!:
		C:\ME\FILEMNGR.DB
		C:\ME\HELP\FILEMNGR.HLZ
		C:\ME\MAC\FILEMNGR.MAC
		C:\ME\SRC\FILEMNGR.S

		Network version users:  The user specific files will
		be as follows (xxx = user id):
			C:\ME\xxx.USR\FILEMNGR.DB

		!!!NOTE: In order for the NAMEIT button to appear in
		the file dialog, you must now add the following to your
		STARTUP macro:

			Load_Macro_File('FILEMNGR');

		Be sure to recompile STARTUP.S after making the change.

	50+ MACROS (assuming you installed all of them):
		We recommend simply re-installing the macros.  However,
		you may simply copy over the desired .S files.  Plus...
		Any of the above .S files that were compiled will also
		have a .MAC file in the MAC subdirectory under the main
		Multi-Edit directory.

THE TEMPLATE LANGUAGE
	Much of our language specific template expansion is now done in
	a special "template language" that allows easy user changes.
	This "language" is explained in detail in TEMPLATE.DOC.

CONFIGURING C INDENT AND TEMPLATE STYLES
	You can modify the C indenting and template expansion to a
	couple of common styles very quickly by changing a couple of
	#defines near the top of C.S (right after the header that
	describes what macros are in the file).   The #defines are
	commented.


CLIPPER USERS
	We have recently improved the DBASE language support to include
	support for the Clipper version 5 dialect.  This includes
	support for "While" instead of "DO While", "End" instead of
	"Endxx", and C style comments "/* */" and "//".  To enable
	these capabilities, you must place the following line in the
	STARTUP.S file:

		Set_Global_Int('!DBASE_DIALECT',1);

	Then you must recompile STARTUP.S.  See the manual for
	details on compiling macros.

MICROSOFT WINDOWS 3.0, OS/2, DESQview
	Multi-Edit works best as a FULL-SCREEN application under
	WINDOWS.  There is a 'PIF' file for use in WINDOWS in the
	Multi-Edit subdirectory (also included is the file ME.ICO,
	which is a Multi-Edit ICON for Windows 3.0).  Multi-Edit also
	works fine in the DOS compatibility box of OS/2 and under
	DESQview.

	For DESQview, set the "Writes directly to screen" and
	"Virtualize Text/Graphics" options to "N" (this is done inside
	DESQview).  The Multi-Edit "/D" command line option must NOT be
	used in this case (if /D is used, both questions should be set
	to "Y").  Also, be sure to NOT set the protection level (in the
	Advanced Setup Screen of DESQview) greater than 1.

	NOTE:  You should allocate at least 350K (preferably 400K) of
	RAM to Multi-Edit when running from WINDOWS or DESQview.

PC-KWIK
	There may be an incompatibility between this caching program and
	Multi-Edit's disk swapping management routines.  Report is that
	their version 1.58 works fine with Multi-Edit.  Some versions
	may require the use of the L- switch in order to work properly.
	Note that some versions of PC-KWIK are also incompatible with
	WINDOW's HIMEM.SYS program.

COREFAST
	The CFTIME scheduler used with this CORE backup utility is not
	compatible with Multi-Edit.

DOS PRINT & MODE
	These DOS commands affect the current state of memory, and like
	all "TSR's", must NOT be run for the first time when shelled out
	of Multi-Edit.  They must be "loaded" before invoking
	Multi-Edit, and then can be run from within the editor.

USER MENU
	Multi-Edit is shipped with a number of macros already on the
	User Menu.  They may be deleted and/or additional programs
	added.

	NoteBook:  Our cool note organizer.

	Convert keystroke macro to macro source code:
		This macro lets you convert keystroke macros to KEY_IN
		statements in the macro language.  See the MACRO
		LANGUAGE REFERENCE GUIDE for detailed information on
		KEY_IN.

	List unassigned keys in EDIT mode:
		This is real handy when you want to assign keys for
		your own Keystroke or other macros.  Tells what keys
		are available.

	Phone - Address list:
		Check out the little phone/address directory we threw
		in.

DATAFLEX
	To compile with Dataflex you must use the provided batch file
	DFLEX.BAT for your compile command line.  For example:
		DFLEX <FILE> <EXT>
	Make sure the CR/LF at eof is turned ON. You will find this
	toggle in the Edit Settings sub-menu of the Install menu.
	While you are in the Install menu, create a Filename Extension
	setup and compiler setup for Dataflex.

CLARION
	To compile with CLARION you must use the provided batch file
	CLARC.BAT for your compile command line.  For example:
		CLARC <FILE>
	(The CLARC.BAT file assumes a .CLA extension)

ALSYS ADA
	To compile with ALSYS ADA you must use the provided batch file
	ADACOMP.BAT for your compile command line.  For example:
		ADACOMP <FILE>
	(The ADACOMP.BAT file assumes a .ADA extension)


	If you use a BATCH file to compile, you will probably have to
	add <NR> to your command line (in Filename Extension Setup -
	Install-Filename extension-F3-Compiler/prog setup) where you
	specify the Batch file, to avoid double re-direction.

HISTORY LISTS
	If you add the following global integer to your STARTUP macro,
	you can set the maximum length of the history list:

		Set_Global_Int("@HISTORY_LENGTH",15);

	The value of 15 shown above is the default.  Any value greater
	than 0 is legal.

		 CONVERTING 5.0 AND 6.x MACROS TO 7.0

If you are working in the MEMAC language, we recommend changing to
CMAC, as MEMAC support is being phased out.  If you chose to do so, the
macro SRCCONV will do most of the conversion for you.  You MUST install
SRCCONV from Module Installation.

The MEMAC.EXE compiler is no longer included with Multi-Edit.  However,
the version 6.x MEMAC compiler is compatible with Multi-Edit 7.0.
Also, MEMAC.EXE is available on CompuServe or our BBS.

NOTE:  The system function calls between MEMAC and CMAC are identical.


There are a few changes to the system function calls (from 5.0 to 6.x)
that may effect your macros:

        TOGGLE_VIDEO            No longer exists!!!!

        VIDEO_MODE              Returns an integer:
                                0 = 25 lines
                                1 = 30/33 lines
                                2 = 43/50 lines

                                255 = #of lines overridden with /X /Y
                                      switches.
	SET_VIDEO_MODE( mode )  New!!
				0 = 25 lines
				1 = 30/33 lines
				2 = 43/50 lines

				Should NOT be used, instead use the
				macro
					SETUP^TGLVID /M=n
				where "n" is the video mode to switch
				to!

	BLOCK_STAT is now a variable.

	PERSISTENT_BLOCKS	If your macro relies on a block
				remaining on while the cursor is moved,
				then you need to save the old status of
				PERSISTENT_BLOCKS, set it to TRUE, and
				then restore it when you are done.  See
				the docs for more info on
				PERSISTENT_BLOCKS.

There are a few changes to the system function calls (from 6.x to 7.0)
that may effect your macros:

	SEARCH_FILE		Documented in the 7.0 addendum

	SET_KEYWORDS		This call has changed extensively.

SET_KEYWORDS( name, case_sens, reserved_word_scan_chars, scan_chars,
	      reserved_words1, reserved_words2, reserved_words3,
	      reserved_words4, special_chars, reserved_words_attr,
	      symbols, symbols_attr, string_chars, string_attr,
	      literal_char, eol_comment, eol_comment_attr,
	      eol_comment_col, eol2_comment, eol2_comment_attr,
	      eol2_comment_col, open_comment1, close_comment1,
	      comment1_attr, open_comment2, close_comment2,
	      comment2_attr, numeric_chars, numeric_attr )  void function

	This function initializes a KEYWORDS data structure.  Not all
	programming languages require every parameter in this data
	structure and any unneeded parameters should be set to a null
	string or a zero integer.

	Name can be any string expression and is what you set
	KEYWORDS_STR to.

	Case_sens is an integer that, if true, will cause Multi-Edit to
	consider the reserved words to be case-sensitive.

	Reserved_word_scan_chars is a string of characters that are
	taken from the first characters of each of the separate words
	in reserved_words1 and reserved_words2.  The reasoning behind
	scan characters is to significantly speed up scanning for
	reserved words, symbols, etc.

	Scan_chars is a string of characters that are taken from all of
	the strings in this structure other than the reserved words.

	Reserved_words1 a set of alphanumeric words separated by
	spaces.  The set must be preceded and followed by a space.  The
	maximum length of the set is 255 characters.

	Reserved_words2,3 and 4 are the same as reserved_words1.  They
	are used if there are more reserved words than will fit in
	reserved_words1.

	Special_Chars should contain any non-alpha-numeric characters
	that appear in any of the reserved words.

	Reserved_words_attr is the color attribute integer value.  All
	color attributes in this data structure are 16-bit integers.
	Bits 0-3 are the foreground color.  Bits 4-7 are the background
	color.  Bit 8 activates the foreground color.  Bit 9 activates
	background color.

	Symbols is a string containing single-character symbols like
	numeric operators, parentheses, braces, etc.

	Symbols_attr is the color attribute for symbols.  See
	reserved_words_attr for an explanation of the color attribute.

	String_chars is a string containing characters that denote
	string constants.  This the single quote (') and/or double
	quote (") in most cases.

	String_attr is the color attribute for string_chars.  See
	reserved_words_attr for an explanation of the color attribute.

	Literal_char:  If the programming language has a special
	character (often called an escape character) that allows you to
	imbed a character from the string_chars parameter (above) in a
	string constant by preceding it with the special character,
	define it here.

	Example:  In C, the escape character is the backslash (\).  If
	you wish to imbed a double quote inside a string constant, you
	would do something like this:  mystr = "This is a quote\"";

	It is the backslash character that should be in the
	literal_char parameter.

	Eol_comment is a sequence of characters that denotes the
	beginning of an end-of-line comment.

	Eol_comment_attr is the color attribute for eol_comment.  See
	reserved_words_attr for an explanation of the color attribute.

	Eol_Comment_Col is the column that a EOL comment must start at
	to be valid.  If it is zero, then the column is ignored.  If it
	is -1, then the eol comment will be matched only if it is the
	first  NON-WHITESPACE character set on the line.

	eol2_comment, eol2_comment_attr, eol2_comment_col are identical
	to the above.

	Open_comment1 is a sequence of characters that denotes the
	start of a multi-line comment

	Close_comment1 is a character sequence that defines the end of
	a multi-line comment.

	Comment1_attr is the color attribute for open_comment1 and
	close_comment1.  See reserved_words_attr for an explanation of
	the color attribute.

	Open_comment2, close_comment2 and comment2_attr are the same as
	above and are used if the language has a second set of
	open/close comment character sequences.

	Numeric_Chars defines character OTHER than 0-9 that are to be
	highlighted as numeric constants.  These characters only count
	if they are the  first character of the item to be highlighted.
	This would be used, for example to have $ highlight hex
	constants in PASCAL.

	Numeric_Chars_Attr is the attribute for highlighting numeric
	constants.


KEY_MACRO_NUM	integer function
	KEY_MACRO_NUM returns the nesting levels of keystroke macros.
	Normally it returns 0.   It returns non-zero if a keystroke
	macro is being executed.




